      "content": "yeah i see. so it basically comes down to the fact that the suburban guy has more \"rehabilitative potential\" because he has a safety net, while the urban guy is seen as more of a \"liability\" because he doesn't? \n\ni'm trying to figure out if there's a way to argue for the urban guy to get the same probation as the suburban guy. if the crime is exactly the same, wouldn't it be unfair to give him a harsher sentence just because his zip code or job history looks \"risky\"? or is that just how the math of sentencing works in real life?",
